    parentName: "p"
  }, "Eliza Sorensen:")), mdx("p", null, "Why is a private entity being able to make money of hashes of child pornography. One of the things we actually did try to get access to photoDNA early on and we were rejected. What do we do as a company? And say I think that's the same with Thorn, we have asked for a list of... What is it? What was the name for that keyword list? Oh, yes, the key word list that you can use against anything that gets posted on your website. Sort of like, if you have certain words, like Lolita, for example, which might ring a bell. Then it'll send an alert or something like that to your moderation team to have it investigated."), mdx("p", null, mdx("em", {
    parentName: "p"
  }, "Ethan Zuckerman:")), mdx("p", null, "Right, so these feel like resources that just should be public resources, right? So the notion should be in creating Switter, in creating Tryst, it makes sense to be able to have access to something where you can check imagery against the database for child sexual abuse imagery. But having that owned by Microsoft or having a built in a way where it's being built by civilians and it's not being done by law enforcement. It's also, as far as I can tell, not being audited, right? It's not being checked around. And here, we've seen sort of civil rights compliance more around databases of terrorist and extremist content. Where you have pushback from Electronic Frontier Foundation and others sort of arguing, \"look, this could be a very helpful thing, but we really need the ability to audit it and make sure that it is what it says it is.\""), mdx("p", null, mdx("em", {
